definition.value: A butenedioic acid in which the C=C double bond has E geometry. It is an intermediate metabolite in the citric acid cycle.
An L-alpha-amino acid; the L-isomer of lysine.

A glyceride that is glycerol in which any two of the hydroxy groups have been acylated. In the structure shown, two of the R groups (positions not specified) are acyl groups while the remaining R group can be either H or an alkyl group.
A UDP-sugar having D-glucose as the sugar component.
Any polysaccharide containing a substantial proportion of aminomonosaccharide residues.
A CMP-N-acyl-beta-neuraminic acid in which the N-acyl group is glycoloyl.
RNA molecules which are essential structural and functional components of ribosomes, the subcellular units responsible for protein synthesis.
The phosphate of choline; and the parent compound of the phosphocholine family.
Any six-carbon monosaccharide which in its linear form contains either an aldehyde group at position 1 (aldohexose) or a ketone group at position 2 (ketohexose).
A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
Any phosphatidylinositol that is phosphorylated at one or more of the hydroxy groups of inositol.
A tocopherol in which the chroman-6-ol core is substituted by methyl groups at positions 7 and 8. It is found particularly in maize (corn) oil and soya bean (soybean) oils.
An alpha-amino acid that is phenylalanine bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 4 on the phenyl ring.
The parent compound of the citrulline class consisting of ornithine having a carbamoyl group at the N(5)-position.
A sialotetraosylceramide having beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)]-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the sialotetraosyl component.
An alpha-amino acid that is glutaric acid bearing a single amino substituent at position 2.
An iron group element atom that has atomic number 26.
Any nucleoside where the sugar component is D-ribose.
An alpha-amino acid that is pentanoic acid bearing two amino substituents at positions 2 and 5.

An iodothyronine compound having iodo substituents at the 3-, 3'- and 5-positions. Although some is produced in the thyroid, most of the 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the body is generated by mono-deiodination of L-thyroxine in the peripheral tissues. Its metabolic activity is about 3 to 5 times that of L-thyroxine. The sodium salt is used in the treatment of hypothyroidism.
That part of DNA or RNA that may be involved in pairing.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1H-imidazole substituted at position C-4 by a 2-aminoethyl group.
A class of aminophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of serine.
A UDP-sugar having D-galactose as the sugar component.
An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having the general formula CnH2n+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms.
A dipeptide comprising of beta-alanine and 3-methyl-L-histidine units.
A vitamin B6 phosphate that is the  phosphoric ester derivative of pyridoxamine.
A phosphatidylinositol bisphosphate in which the two phosphate groups are at C-4 and C-5 of the inositol moiety which has the 1D-myo configuration.
A phosphate ion that is the conjugate base of hydrogenphosphate.
Sphingosine substituted at the 1-hydroxy group by a D-glucosyl group and at the 2-amino group by an acyl group.
A ribosyl or deoxyribosyl derivative of a pyrimidine or purine base in which C-3 and C-5 of the ribose ring are engaged in formation of a cyclic mono-, di-, tri- or tetra-phosphate.
Any of a group of glycosaminoglycans with repeating units consisting of variously sulfated beta1->4-linked L-iduronyl-(alpha1->3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine units.
A gluconate having D-configuration.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of phenylacetic acid.
The monophosphate ester obtained by condensation of phosphoric acid with the primary hydroxy group of pyridoxal.
A D-glucopyranuronate that has alpha configuration at the anomeric centre.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from the deprotonation of the two carboxy groups of 5-methyltetrahydrofolic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.
Any fatty acid containing two carboxy groups.
Any fatty acid that contains 2 carboxylic groups. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
